**3G. Optimization Opportunities Section Audit — COMPLETE (Feb 9, 2026)**

**Files audited:** 4 | **Bugs fixed:** 8 | **Logic rewritten:** 1 function | **Component rewritten:** 1

**FIXES APPLIED:**
- `types/index.ts`: Added `OptimizationType`, `OptimizationDifficulty`, `OptimizationPriority` types. Added `savingsPercent`, `actionLabel`, `actionUrl`, `difficulty`, `priority`, `relatedSection` fields to `OptimizationOpportunity`. Note in `Optimization.totalPotentialSavings` that savings are de-duplicated.
- `orchestrator.ts` `getOptimizationOpportunities()`: **REWRITTEN** — was 50 lines with 2 opportunity types and hardcoded tradeoffs. Now 200+ lines generating up to 7 opportunity types by synthesizing data from ALL prior analysis steps:
  1. **Country switch** — uses real transit days, supplier counts, data quality, cost trends from country comparison. Relative savings threshold (2% or $500, whichever greater) instead of hardcoded $1000.
  2. **FTA qualification** — identifies specific FTA name, links to FTA Calculator with pre-filled HTS code. De-duplicated from country switch when same country.
  3. **Classification review** — triggered when confidence <85% AND alternative HTS codes have materially lower duty rates (>3pp). Estimates savings from rate difference.
  4. **Section 232 exclusion** — triggered from compliance Section 232 alert. Links to Commerce portal.
  5. **AD/CVD mitigation** — triggered when AD/CVD warning exists AND an AD/CVD-free alternative country has savings.
  6. **High tariff alert** — triggered when effective rate >50% and no other opportunities found. Identifies biggest cost driver layer.
  7. **Duty drawback** — triggered for high-duty products (>30% rate, >$5000 duty). Recovery of up to 99% if goods re-exported.
- `orchestrator.ts`: **BUG FIX** — `totalPotentialSavings` was naively summing all opportunity savings, double-counting when FTA country = country switch country. Now properly de-duplicates: sourcing strategies (country switch, FTA, AD/CVD) are mutually exclusive (take max), classification review and Section 232 exclusion are additive.
- `orchestrator.ts`: **BUG FIX** — Country switch title used raw ISO codes (`Switch from CN to VN`) instead of country names.
- `orchestrator.ts`: **BUG FIX** — Tradeoffs were generic hardcoded strings. Now data-driven from country comparison (transit time diff, supplier count, data quality, cost trend).
- `orchestrator.ts`: Function signature updated to accept `Classification` and `Compliance` objects (was only using `htsCode` string and ignoring compliance data entirely).
- `OptimizationSection.tsx`: **REWRITTEN** — removed emoji number indicators (`1️⃣`), replaced with color-coded numbered badges matching opportunity type. Added difficulty tags (Quick Win / Moderate Effort / Strategic Change). Added priority tags. Tradeoffs rendered in amber warning box. Each opportunity has contextual CTA button linking to relevant tool. Dead CTAs ("Generate Optimization Report", "Schedule Consultation") removed. Green gradient savings card replaced with teal-50 card matching design system. Uses `EmptyState` component when no opportunities found.
- `ResultsContainer.tsx`: Collapse header shows `Tag color="green"` with savings amount when >0, `Tag color="blue"` with suggestion count when opportunities exist but savings=0, or `Tag color="green" Optimized` when no opportunities at all (was showing "$0 savings" which looked broken).

**ARCHITECTURE NOTES (3G):**
- Optimization is the synthesis layer — it should summarize actionable insights from all 5 prior steps. Previously it only used country comparison data. Now it cross-references classification confidence, tariff layer breakdown, compliance alerts, and country comparison alternatives.
- The de-duplication logic is important: country switch, FTA qualification, and AD/CVD mitigation are all "change your sourcing country" strategies. If you switch to Vietnam for cost savings AND Vietnam happens to have an FTA, those aren't additive savings — they're the same move. Only the best sourcing savings counts.
- Classification review and Section 232 exclusion ARE additive because they change the tariff rate regardless of sourcing country.
- Duty drawback is excluded from totals because it only applies to re-exported goods.

